<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="224" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,798,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1446,1471]" pageId="5" pageNumber="224">Etymology.</emphasis>
This specific epithet is derived from the Latin word “ 
<taxonomicName box="[946,1009,1447,1470]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Thagria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="224" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crena">
<emphasis box="[946,1009,1447,1470]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="224">crena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, referring to the notched apex of the ventral paraphysis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="224" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,798,1579]" pageId="5" pageNumber="224">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1518,1543]" pageId="5" pageNumber="224">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species belongs to species group with broad clypellus and colorful appearance. It is similar to the last species, but has the ventral paraphysis notched apically and with a distinctive basal process.
</paragraph>
